nalyzing bridge call and coverage**\\n\\nI’m thinking that the bridge call can directly invoke the method from the helper under the library package. I have a `SimpleTagSupportLineCoverage` where the return value should be at line 183, which is good since it aligns with the `SourceFile` attribute. But now I’m wondering if I can include this bridge class in the libraryClasses. My concern is whether JaCoCo will include test classes in the report and how that could affect overall coverage metrics. It feels complex, but I just need to clarify these details!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build issues with sealed packages**\\n\\nI'm concerned that the build might fail because the test source package has a class in `javax.servlet`, and that package is sealed due to Java modules. Since Java 9, `javax` is prohibited on the classpath, which complicates things. While split packages might work, I need to ensure that the public bridge is at the top level in the library package, as being in the same package could violate rules. I'll have to think about the user's perspective on this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Testing implementation plans**\\n\\nI’m considering implementing a bridge and helper method. It sounds like a solid plan! I’ll also need to test the import from the library package to ensure everything works as it should. It’s important to double-check that the integration runs smoothly. I wonder if there are any specific testing strategies I should use. Let's make sure these elements function together seamlessly for the best outcome!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kXlSpN5Y3lw2mcxCg3qlteeJ|fc_0f2554e6489e5efb0169f5265495c8819586fd0311684828f9", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "mkdir -p tests/src/jspapi/jsp-api/2.0-20040521/src/test/java/javax/servlet/jsp/tagext\npython - <<'PY'\nfrom pathlib import Path\npath = Path('tests/src/jspapi/jsp-api/2.0-20040521/src/test/java/javax/servlet/jsp/tagext/SimpleTagSupport.java')